Day 24: POST APIs (React + Spring Boot)
Goal

Learn how to send data from a React form to a Spring Boot backend using Axios POST requests.

Flow
React Form
    ↓
Axios POST Request
    ↓
Spring Boot REST API
    ↓
Save Data
    ↓
Response Back to React
Step 1: Spring Boot POST API
Employee.java
public class Employee {

    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private String department;

    public Employee() {
    }

    public Employee(Long id, String name, String department) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.department = department;
    }

    // Getters and Setters
}
EmployeeController.java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/employees")
@CrossOrigin(origins = "http://localhost:5173")
public class EmployeeController {

    @PostMapping
    public Employee saveEmployee(@RequestBody Employee employee) {

        System.out.println(employee.getName());
        System.out.println(employee.getDepartment());

        return employee;
    }
}
Step 2: Create Service Layer
EmployeeService.js
import axios from "axios";

const API_URL = "http://localhost:8080/api/employees";

export const saveEmployee = (employee) => {
    return axios.post(API_URL, employee);
};
Step 3: Create Form Component
EmployeeForm.jsx
import { useState } from "react";
import { saveEmployee } from "../services/EmployeeService";

function EmployeeForm() {

    const [name, setName] = useState("");
    const [department, setDepartment] = useState("");

    const handleSubmit = async (e) => {

        e.preventDefault();

        const employee = {
            name,
            department
        };

        try {

            const response = await saveEmployee(employee);

            console.log(response.data);

            alert("Employee Saved Successfully");

            setName("");
            setDepartment("");

        } catch (error) {

            console.log(error);

            alert("Failed to save employee");
        }
    };

    return (
        <div>

            <h2>Add Employee</h2>

            <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>

                <div>
                    <label>Name:</label>
                    <input
                        type="text"
                        value={name}
                        onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
                    />
                </div>

                <br />

                <div>
                    <label>Department:</label>
                    <input
                        type="text"
                        value={department}
                        onChange={(e) => setDepartment(e.target.value)}
                    />
                </div>

                <br />

                <button type="submit">
                    Save Employee
                </button>

            </form>

        </div>
    );
}

export default EmployeeForm;
Step 4: Use Component in App.jsx
import EmployeeForm from "./components/EmployeeForm";

function App() {

    return (
        <>
            <EmployeeForm />
        </>
    );
}

export default App;
How POST Request Works

When user enters:

Name = John
Department = IT

React sends:

{
  "name": "John",
  "department": "IT"
}

Spring Boot receives it through:

@RequestBody Employee employee
Add Validation
if (!name || !department) {
    alert("All fields are required");
    return;
}

Place it before calling the API.

Using .then() Instead of async/await
saveEmployee(employee)
    .then(response => {
        alert("Employee Saved");
    })
    .catch(error => {
        console.log(error);
    });
Interview Questions
What is @RequestBody?

Used to convert incoming JSON into a Java object.

@PostMapping
public Employee saveEmployee(
        @RequestBody Employee employee) {
}
Why call e.preventDefault()?

Prevents the browser from refreshing the page when the form is submitted.

e.preventDefault();
What is a Controlled Component?

A form element whose value is controlled by React state.

